:QUOTE
Every espresso variable is connected. Pull on one thread and the others move.

:INFO
What Dialing In Actually Means
Dialing in is the process of adjusting grind size, dose, and yield until a \
shot tastes right. It is not a one-time setup. Every new bag of beans \
requires a fresh dial-in. Roast date, humidity, and even altitude shift \
the variables.

:IMAGE
grind-chart.jpg

:INFO
The Three Variables That Matter
Grind size controls how fast water flows through the puck. Dose is the \
weight of dry coffee you put in the basket. Yield is the weight of liquid \
espresso in the cup. These three numbers define every shot.
|
:QUOTE
Taste is the final test. Numbers are just a starting point.

:COUNTER.half
9 Bars Pressure
|
:COUNTER.half
93 Celsius Water Temp

:PATH
Start With a Known Recipe
Use a 1 to 2 ratio as your baseline. 18 grams of ground coffee should \
yield 36 grams of liquid espresso. Set a target time of 25 to 30 seconds \
from first drip to stopping the shot.

:PATH
Pull a Shot and Taste It
Do not adjust anything until you taste the shot. Sour means under \
extracted. Bitter means over extracted. Bland and watery means the grind \
is too coarse or the dose is too low.

:PATH
Adjust One Variable at a Time
If the shot is sour, make the grind finer. If bitter, make it coarser. \
Change only one thing between shots. Changing two variables at once makes \
it impossible to know what caused the improvement.

:IMAGE
extraction-color.jpg

:PATH
Dial in the Yield Last
Once the flavor is close, adjust yield to balance strength and body. A \
longer yield gives more volume but thins the shot. A shorter yield \
concentrates it. Most people land between 30 and 40 grams out from an \
18 gram dose.

:COUNTER.half
25 to 30 Seconds
|
:COUNTER.half
1 to 2 Dose Ratio

:INFO
When to Stop Adjusting
A dialed-in shot is consistent across three pulls in a row. If your shots \
vary widely without changing anything, the issue is likely technique: \
uneven distribution, channeling, or inconsistent tamping pressure.
|
:QUOTE
A flat, even puck is the only foundation a good shot can be built on.

:CHECKLIST
Puck Prep Checklist
[ ] Dose to within 0.2 grams of your target weight
[ ] Distribute grounds evenly before tamping (Weiss Distribution Technique or a \
finger sweep)
[ ] Tamp level with 15 to 20 kg of pressure
[ ] Check the basket rim is clean before locking in

:NOTE
Channeling
Channeling happens when water finds a path of least resistance through the \
puck instead of flowing evenly. It produces sour, thin shots with fast \
run times. The fix is even distribution and a level tamp, not a finer \
grind. A bottomless portafilter makes channeling visible immediately.

